    source: "WEG40095 Galaxy Guide 6: Tramp Freighters p.51",
    summary: "Eliad is a world of exiled nobility. When the Emperor overthrew the Old Republic, he removed a number of nobles from power and offered them a bargain: permanent exile in exchange for keeping much of their wealth. Roughly 300,000 nobles now live here, attended by servants and huge numbers of droids, spread widely across the planet's varied terrain. They have built palaces and villas far out of sight of each other, some replicating the castles of their homeworlds. These families have been wealthy for generations — intelligent, sophisticated, and educated — but are slowly rotting under the weight of their own worthlessness, exactly as the Emperor intended. Immensely rich with nothing productive to spend on, the bored nobles engage in increasingly elaborate entertainments.",
    locations: "Spaceport (located in the Jesart desert, southern hemisphere, far from Human settlements). Imperial Consulate at spaceport. Noble palaces and villas scattered across the planet. Replicas of homeworld castles.",
    ofNote: "The Empire maintains a Lancer-class frigate in orbit crewed mainly by mercenaries with Imperial officers and 100 stormtroopers. 800 stormtroopers guard the spaceport ensuring no noble leaves the planet. All communications monitored by Imperial consulate. Ships leaving are searched thoroughly; ships arriving are rarely searched. Anti-Imperial sentiment exists but is muted — the older nobles who control everything don't want to provoke the Empire. Innovative traders can profit by devising expensive amusements for the bored nobility."
