    source: "WEG40095 Galaxy Guide 6: Tramp Freighters p.58",
    summary: "Yelsain is a very large forest planet with lower than average gravity due to the absence of heavy metals. It sports truly immense trees, some as tall as 400 meters, and a high-oxygen atmosphere that creates spectacular nightly thunderstorms. The settlers — colonists from Adarlon who rejected its opulence — live high in the gigantic trees in houses connected by wood and rope pathways, deliberately choosing a rustic life while maintaining access to high technology. They till fields with animal-drawn plows yet use communicators, air-cars, and advanced medicine. Yelsain's universities are among the finest in the Cluster, and nearly everyone has advanced training in a specialized field. The inhabitants revere wood and nature, constructing almost everything from wood including air speeders. Virtually everyone carries a weapon, duels are common, and visitors learn to be polite quickly. The famous 'tree-rangers' of Yelsain are well-loved in holos across the galaxy, though the settlers themselves hate this popularity.",
    locations: "Tradetown (small settlement around the spaceport, mostly offworlders, only town of any size). Tree communities across the northern continent (houses in gigantic trees, wood and rope pathways between branches, universities in the trees). Annual Grand Moot (huge open field north of Tradetown, week-long trade gathering attended by half the planet's population). Southern islands (dangerous — tremendous hurricanes and deadly wildlife).",
    ofNote: "Government forbids taxation and paid officials — essentially government itself is forbidden by law. Crime is handled by 'meetin's' — drumhead courts of armed settlers. Worst crimes: murder (not fair fights), rape, assault, pollution, theft. Punishments range from beatings to hard labor to banishment on southern thunder islands (virtual death sentence). The Empire imposes a 20% tax on all trade rather than trying to collect from the settlers directly — sending troops into the woods after well-armed, fearless Humans proved too costly. Vehemently anti-Imperial; many Jedi were recruited from Yelsain, and people with Force knowledge may still live deep in the forests. The annual Moot is prime trading opportunity — Tyrellian ale sold for 200 cr/barrel at the last one. Hand-carved wooden tables from Yelsain are luxury items elsewhere. Trogliths and garaths are the most dangerous creatures."
