    source: "WEG40131 The Thrawn Trilogy Sourcebook p.119",
    summary: "Jomark is the second of six worlds orbiting a medium-sized sun, and the only one capable of supporting life. The planet is mostly ocean, with one small continent — Kalish — and an endless number of smaller islands. The colonists came during one of the Old Republic expansions a few thousand years ago. Like many colonies of the period, it was quickly forgotten, precipitating a slide into primitive technology and superstition. The human colonists found a rich world full of paradise islands and crystal water. Even after generations, they still call themselves colonists, though few understand what the term means. They are excellent fishermen, sea farmers, and sailors with an industrial level of technology. Most do not believe in starships and other worlds, though their legends tell them they came from space. They have settled only a quarter of the world's land mass, mostly areas closest to Kalish.",
    locations: "High Castle (short, dirty alien castle of unknown original purpose, nestled between two large crags on an ancient volcanic rim overlooking Rim Lake 400 meters below; held in awe by the colonists; used by Joruus C'baoth as his seat of power while ruling the world). Rim Lake (almost perfectly ring-shaped lake formed inside the remains of a cone-shaped volcano; a smaller cone forms a dark island in its center, used as a well-hidden landing site for Imperial shuttles). Kalish (the small main continent; most population lives along the coast with a few smaller interior settlements).",
    ofNote: "Jomark was the perfect place for Joruus C'baoth to set his trap for Luke Skywalker — just the sort of world a Jedi Master would choose to hide on, with its last star chart update over 15 years old. C'baoth ruled the colonists from the High Castle, using the Force to awe the superstitious population. The dark island in Rim Lake's center served as a hidden landing site for Thrawn's Imperial shuttles. After Luke's brief visit and departure with Mara Jade, C'baoth abandoned the world to set his own plans in motion. The colonists were more than glad to see him leave. The colonists stay away from alien relics, considering them haunted — they do not wish to disturb whatever alien spirits may reside within the strange constructs."
