    source: "WEG40131 The Thrawn Trilogy Sourcebook p.122",
    summary: "Kashyyyk is a jungle planet of unmatched beauty and endless danger. Massive trees cover its surface, their branches intertwining to form an almost continuous forest from the base of the huge trunks to the tops of the highest branches. Life developed throughout this skyward jungle, pushing ever upward from the dark surface toward the sun. The planet's ecosystem is divided into several horizontal levels, one above the other. The Wookiees share the uppermost level with a variety of flying and tree-dwelling creatures. The natural environment becomes increasingly more hostile as one travels down through the levels — the lowest levels serve as the domain of fearsome predators which even Wookiees tend to avoid. The jungle is also home to many beneficial plants and animals, including the delicious kroyie birds which are hunted for food.",
    locations: "Rwookrrorro (one of Kashyyyk's most beautiful metropolitan centers; a true city covering more than a square kilometer, nestled atop a tight ring of wroshyr trees; multi-leveled buildings laid out in wide, straight avenues; hangs as though suspended in mid-air, filling the gaps between massive trees; held up by incredibly strong interlocked wroshyr branches; sweeping colored lights surround the city attracting kroyie birds for hunting). Wookiee Tree Cities (massive cities built within the highest branches, smoothly integrating practical technology with natural beauty).",
    ofNote: "During the height of the Empire, Kashyyyk was under martial law. Imperial garrisons dotted the planet and ships maintained constant orbit. Wookiees were enslaved and forced to work in Imperial slave camps because of their great strength and mechanical talents, kept in line by threats of violence against their families. Imperial law made free Wookiees illegal — any found outside Kashyyyk or work camps were considered outlaws. Today Kashyyyk is once again free, and the Wookiees have begun to allow non-Wookiee traders to visit, though an undercurrent of resentment toward humans lingers from their treatment under the Empire."
